    <bioghist>
      <head>Biographical/Historical Information
</head>
      <p>John L. Heatwole was born in 1948 in Washington, D.C. In 1974 he moved to the Shenandoah Valley, where his family had roots, to take a job as woodcarver at the Virginia Craftsmen Furniture Company in
Harrisonburg. Three years later he opened his own shop in Bridgewater and began working for himself. Self-taught, drawing on folklore and family stories for themes for his carvings, and using only hand tools and a
secret color staining process, Heatwole became widely recognized as an artist of note.
</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Content
</head>
      <p>This collection contains the personal papers of sculptor John L. Heatwole relevant to his work as an artist, during the years 1973-1995.
</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement
</head>
      <p>The order imposed by the creator was generally maintained. Major groupings are: I. Diaries. II. Letters (Incoming). III. Activities. IV. Works about Heatwole. V. Photos. VI. Sketches - Oversize
</p>
    </arrangement>
